    {
      "id": "commentary",
      "html": "<h2>commentary</h2>  <p>These two Jewish epitaphs may not come from Catania: in describing the Biscari collection, Ferrara gives an imprecise indication of the provenance of this inscription and the structure <span class=\"lang\" lang=\"grc\">ἔνθαδε κεῖται ὁ δεῖνα ἐτῶν</span> is rather typical of the inscriptions from the Monteverde catacombs and not attested elsewhere in Catania. On the provenance, see the discussion in Korhonen 2001: 90-93. In any case, a Jewish community is well attested in Catania, as IMusCatania 228 = <a href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000781\" target=\"_blank\">ISic000781</a> of the 4th cent. CE confirms. The two girls were probably related (perhaps sisters). Both names are attested in the Jewish environment: both Leontia, probably a Jewish translation of Judith attested in CIJ 369 (Rome), and Kalliope, attested in BS II 136, 137, 200 (Beth She’arim, see also the Christian inscriptions of Syracuse IGCVO 948, 1321), however, are also popular among non-Jews (on both names, see Rutgers 1997: 249-250).</p>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "bibliography",
      "html": "<h2>bibliography</h2>  <ul><li> 51.1199 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796</a>  </li><li> 46.1243 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000796</a>  </li><li> 1(2).650 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001385\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001385</a>  </li><li> Castelli 1769 174 no.71 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002084\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002084</a>  </li><li> Castelli 1784 185 no.73 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002083\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002083</a>  </li><li> Ferrara 1829 351 no.2 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002005\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002005</a>  </li><li> Kirchhoff 1877 9494 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001249\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001249</a>  </li><li> Kaibel 1890 <a href=\"https://clio.columbia.edu/catalog/6873760\" target=\"_blank\">536</a>  <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001072\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001072</a>  </li><li> Ferrua 1938 72 no.2 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002004\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002004</a>  </li><li> Wilson 1990 310-311 fig.264b <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001509\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001509</a>  </li><li> 1993 no.146 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000166\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000166</a>  </li><li> Gebbia 1996 68 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002240\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002240</a>  </li><li> Korhonen 2004 364 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000028\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10000028</a>  </li></ul>  <ul><li> Rutgers 1997 248 no.29, 249-250 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001614\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001614</a>  </li><li> Korhonen 2001 90-93 <a href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001425\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001425</a>  </li></ul>  "
    },
    {
      "id": "handnote",
      "html": " Letters with serifs: Α, Δ, Λ with extended serifs, Α with broken bar, lunate Ε, cursive Ω. The supraline indicates the abbreviation of ν. In the lower corner of the stone are two menorah and a conical figure, perhaps an ethrog (a type of citron, used in the festival of Sukkot) or an amphora. According to Ferrare, the symbol can represent a shofar (a small ram's-horn trumpet). Kaibel did not understand this symbol, interpreting it as part of a Υ.<p> Lines 1-9  11-21  Interlineation line 1 to 2  not recorded  </p>"
    },
